bbc news environment correspondent richard black traces key milestones, scientific discoveries, technical innovations political action. 1712 - british ironmonger thomas newcomen invents first widely used steam engine, paving way industrial revolution industrial scale use coal. 1800 - world population reaches one billion. 1824 - french physicist joseph fourier describes earth's natural "greenhouse effect". writes: "the temperature [of earth] augmented interposition atmosphere, heat state light finds less resistance penetrating air, re-passing air converted non-luminous heat." 1861 - irish physicist john tyndall shows water vapour certain gases create greenhouse effect. "this aqueous vapour blanket necessary vegetable life england clothing man," concludes. century later, honoured prominent uk climate research organisation - tyndall centre - named him. 1886 - karl benz unveils motorwagen, often regarded first true automobile. 1896 - swedish chemist svante arrhenius concludes industrial-age coal burning enhance natural greenhouse effect. suggests might beneficial future generations. conclusions likely size "man-made greenhouse" ballpark - degrees celsius doubling co2 - modern-day climate models. 1900 - another swede, knut angstrom, discovers even tiny concentrations found atmosphere, co2 strongly absorbs parts infrared spectrum. although realise significance, angstrom shown trace gas produce greenhouse warming. 1927 - carbon emissions fossil fuel burning industry reach one billion tonnes per year. 1930 - human population reaches two billion. 1938 - using records 147 weather stations around world, british engineer guy callendar shows temperatures risen previous century. also shows co2 concentrations increased period, suggests caused warming. "callendar effect" widely dismissed meteorologists. 1955 - using new generation equipment including early computers, us researcher gilbert plass analyses detail infrared absorption various gases. concludes doubling co2 concentrations would increase temperatures 3-4c. 1957 - us oceanographer roger revelle chemist hans suess show seawater absorb additional co2 entering atmosphere, many assumed. revelle writes: "human beings carrying large scale geophysical experiment..." 1958 - using equipment developed himself, charles david (dave) keeling begins systematic measurements atmospheric co2 mauna loa hawaii antarctica. within four years, project - continues today - provides first unequivocal proof co2 concentrations rising. 1960 - human population reaches three billion. 1965 - us president's advisory committee panel warns greenhouse effect matter "real concern". 1972 - first un environment conference, stockholm. climate change hardly registers agenda, centres issues chemical pollution, atomic bomb testing whaling. united nations environment programme (unep) formed result. 1975 - human population reaches four billion. 1975 - us scientist wallace broecker puts term "global warming" public domain title scientific paper. 1987 - human population reaches five billion 1987 - montreal protocol agreed, restricting chemicals damage ozone layer. although established climate change mind, greater impact greenhouse gas emissions kyoto protocol. 1988 - intergovernmental panel climate change (ipcc) formed collate assess evidence climate change. 1989 - uk prime minister margaret thatcher - possessor chemistry degree - warns speech un "we seeing vast increase amount carbon dioxide reaching atmosphere... result change future likely fundamental widespread anything known hitherto." calls global treaty climate change. 1989 - carbon emissions fossil fuel burning industry reach six billion tonnes per year. 1990 - ipcc produces first assessment report. concludes temperatures risen 0.3-0.6c last century, humanity's emissions adding atmosphere's natural complement greenhouse gases, addition would expected result warming. 1992 - earth summit rio de janeiro, governments agree united framework convention climate change. key objective "stabilization greenhouse gas concentrations atmosphere level would prevent dangerous anthropogenic interference climate system". developed countries agree return emissions 1990 levels. 1995 - ipcc second assessment report concludes balance evidence suggests "a discernible human influence" earth's climate. called first definitive statement humans responsible climate change. 1997 - kyoto protocol agreed. developed nations pledge reduce emissions average 5% period 2008-12, wide variations targets individual countries. us senate immediately declares ratify treaty. 1998 - strong el nino conditions combine global warming produce warmest year record. average global temperature reached 0.52c mean period 1961-90 (a commonly used baseline). 1998 - publication controversial "hockey stick" graph indicating modern-day temperature rise northern hemisphere unusual compared last 1,000 years. work would later subject two enquiries instigated us congress. 1999 - human population reaches six billion. 2001 - president george w bush removes us kyoto process. 2001 - ipcc third assessment report finds "new stronger evidence" humanity's emissions greenhouse gases main cause warming seen second half 20th century. 2005 - kyoto protocol becomes international law countries still inside it. 2005 - uk prime minister tony blair selects climate change priority terms chair g8 president eu. 2006 - stern review concludes climate change could damage global gdp 20% left unchecked - curbing would cost 1% global gdp. 2006 - carbon emissions fossil fuel burning industry reach eight billion tonnes per year. 2007 - ipcc's fourth assessment report concludes 90% likely humanity's emissions greenhouse gases responsible modern-day climate change. 2007 - ipcc former us vice-president al gore receive nobel peace prize "for efforts build disseminate greater knowledge man-made climate change, lay foundations measures needed counteract change". 2007 - un negotiations bali, governments agree two-year "bali roadmap" aimed hammering new global treaty end 2009. 2008 - half century beginning observations mauna loa, keeling project shows co2 concentrations risen 315 parts per million (ppm) 1958 380ppm 2008. 2008 - two months taking office, incoming us president barack obama pledges "engage vigorously" rest world climate change. 2009 - china overtakes us world's biggest greenhouse gas emitter - although us remains well ahead per-capita basis. 2009 - computer hackers download huge tranche emails server university east anglia's climatic research unit release internet, leading "climategate" affair. 2009 - 192 governments convene un climate summit copenhagen expectations new global agreement high; leave controversial political declaration, copenhagen accord. 2010 - developed countries begin contributing $30bn, three-year deal "fast start finance" help "green" economies adapt climate impacts. 2010 - series reviews "climategate" ipcc ask openness, clear scientists malpractice. 2010 - un summit mexico collapse, feared, ends agreements number issues. 2011 - new analysis earth's temperature record scientists concerned "climategate" allegations proves planet's land surface really warmed last century. 2011 - human population reaches seven billion. 2011 - data shows concentrations greenhouse gases rising faster previous years. 2012 - arctic sea ice reaches minimum extent 3.41 million sq km (1.32 million sq mi), record lowest summer cover since satellite measurements began 1979. 2013 - mauna loa observatory hawaii reports daily mean concentration co2 atmosphere surpassed 400 parts per million (ppm) first time since measurements began 1958. 2013 - first part ipcc's fifth assessment report says scientists 95% certain humans "dominant cause" global warming since 1950s.
