kremlin's international media operation appears going strength strength two recent high-profile launches pipeline. also coming increased scrutiny lack editorial balance accusations deliberately using disinformation counter divide west. spanking new press centre moscow 10 november, controversial tv news anchor dmitry kiselev, also head rossiya segodnya (russia today) news agency, unveiled sputnik - kremlin's latest foray international news arena. planned network media hubs 30 cities, sputnik new brand radio station voice russia foreign-language operations ria novosti news service, taken rossiya segodnya launched last december. kiselev said new project aimed global audience "tired aggressive propaganda promoting unipolar world want different perspective". relentless denunciation west demonisation ukrainians fascists state tv, hardly practised purveyor "aggressive propaganda" kiselev himself. sputnik launch came less fortnight kremlin's international tv channel rt (formerly known russia today) unveiled dedicated news service viewers uk. editor-in-chief margarita simonyan (who holds position rossiya segodnya) said rt uk would seek "promote debate new ways thinking british issues". rt's funding set rise 2015 $330m (£210m; €264m). said planning add french german operations existing services english, spanish arabic. rt uk's debut greeted barrage criticism british press. writing observer, nick cohen accused channel spreading conspiracy theories "prostitution journalism". meanwhile, times, oliver kamm called broadcast regulator ofcom act "den deceivers". oliver kamm long wait. 10 november, ofcom found rt guilty violating broadcasting code's "due impartiality" rules coverage ukraine crisis early march. rejected rt's contention station challenges "established" view uk somehow exempt normal broadcast requirements. view past violations, put channel notice future breaches may result "statutory sanction", could include fines, even suspension revocation rt's broadcast licence. president putin, rt spearheading russia's bid challenge "anglo-saxon monopoly" global news. but, according recent report us journalist michael weiss uk-based writer tv producer peter pomerantsev, part strategy disinformation aimed countering dividing west. entitled "the menace unreality: kremlin weaponises information, culture money", report produced aegis us-based institute modern russia (imr), part-funded members family former oil tycoon putin opponent mikhail khodorkovsky.. adapting techniques inherited old kgb, say authors, rt makes extensive use conspiracy theories serve undermine "reality-based discourse". this, argue, creates conditions kremlin advance disinformation "confuse situations critical junctures". give examples spurious rt report jews fleeing ukraine anti-semitism, equally bogus insinuations us think tank advising ukrainian president poroshenko carry ethnic cleansing, spreading conspiracy theories concerning downing malaysian airliner mh17 east ukraine july. according weiss pomerantsev, kind media manipulation amounts "weaponisation information", phrase also used relation russia mark galeotti, professor global affairs new york university. ms simonyan insists rt different major news broadcasters. responding ofcom ruling, said bbc also guilty "bias" reporting ukraine, well coverage issues. statement posted rt's website, said broadcasters would also change way operate, "if double standards avoided". weiss pomerantsev, meanwhile, came fire anonymous article pro-kremlin english-language website russia insider. part political critique, part personalised attack, article accuses members "russophobic hack pack" also includes edward lucas economist us journalist anne applebaum. ordinary russians appear hold similar views. poll published 12 november independent levada centre indicated 88% population believe usa western countries waging information war russia. 4% dissented view. bbc monitoring reports analyses news tv, radio, web print media around world. follow bbc monitoring twitter facebook.
antes de que acabe la semana, te planteamos un nuevo desafío mental. escapa de este laberinto de la rutina, de paso pon funcionar esas neuronas. al caminar por este laberinto debes decidir en cada intersección qué dirección tomar, solo tienes dos alternativas: el camino de la derecha el de la izquierda. si sigues la ruta de escape correcta, pasarás por seis intersecciones. ¿cuál es la probabilidad de que escojas el camino correcto? baja para descubrir la respuesta la respuesta la probabilidad es 1 de 64. detalles de una de las posibles soluciones este problema: 2 x 2 x 2 x 2 x 2 x 2 = 64 es decir, hay una posibilidad en 64 de que tomes la ruta correcta. acertijo vía el programa todayde radio 4 de la bbc proporcionado por el dr. steve humble, director de educación de la universidad de newcastle.
new vaccine could prevent nine-in-10 cases typhoid fever recommended world health organization. experts say could "huge impact" 22 million cases, 220,000 deaths, typhoid year. crucially works children, high-risk infection, unlike typhoid vaccines. hoped vaccine could eventually help countries eliminate typhoid. typhoid fever caused salmonella typhi bacteria patients have: bacteria highly contagious spread contaminated food water. infection common countries poor sanitation lack clean water, particularly south asia sub-saharan africa. two typhoid vaccines already approved help reduce number cases, none licensed children age two. decision recommend new conjugate typhoid vaccine made who's strategic advisory group experts immunization (sage). prof alejandro cravioto, chairman sage, said: "for first time think effective vaccine." sage recommended vaccine given children aged six-months old said catch-up campaigns focusing children 15 years old also take place. prof cravioto said vaccine vital world "reaching limit" current treatments due "crazy amount" antibiotic resistance typhoid bacterium acquired. data clinical trial vaccine, carried university oxford, published last month lancet medical journal. "challenge study" gave vaccine 112 people deliberately infected (challenged) typhoid-causing bacteria. approach gives clear picture vaccine's effectiveness without immunise thousands people. showed vaccine 87% effective. prof andrew pollard, ran trials, told bbc news website: "it could huge impact. "if rolled communities, must possible prevent majority cases also interrupts transmission, hasn't shown yet, could eliminated regions." gavi, global body pays vaccines 68 low middle-income countries, considering whether add typhoid vaccine. dr seth berkley, chief executive gavi, said: "not could vaccine save lives, could also prove valuable weapon fight antimicrobial resistance." antibiotics, typhoid killed one-in-five people infected. growing levels typhoid resistant drugs. follow