ancient human skull discovered papua new guinea likely belonged world's oldest-known tsunami victim, scientists say. skull discovered 1929 near town aitape incorrectly attributed homo erectus species, ancestor modern humans. however, scientists say area coastal lagoon hit tsunami 6,000 years ago. believe skull belonged person died tsunami. discovery came international team compared sediments area soil nearby region hit devastating tsunami 1998. "while bones well studied, little attention previously paid sediments unearthed," said first author prof james goff, university new south wales. "geographical similarities" sediments showed humans experienced tsunamis area thousands years, said. "we conclude person died long ago probably oldest-known tsunami victim world," said prof goff. scientists said also possible person died buried tsunami happened. research involved studying grain size composition sediments. among microscopic organisms ocean, similar ones found 1998 tsunami killed 2,000 people. team also performed radiocarbon dating, method used accurately determine age artefacts. researchers said findings, published journal plos one, raise questions whether archaeological discoveries coastal areas re-evaluated.
