almost three years, home city mosul occupation so-called islamic state (is), tahani salih kept daily diary documenting crimes. tahani, 27, filled almost 500 pages experiences family friends, well hopes dreams time would defeated. "just neighbourhood liberated, began harass people force way homes carry searches. one day took hand-written pages started reread them, shocked," said. "i realised content could put life family risk, well people mentioned diary. choice destroy papers. "i sat down, started burn one page time. later, blamed hiding diary burying garden." although diary gone, tahani remembers every word plans made. defeated, tahani throwing putting place. young woman - trained supported institute war peace reporting (iwpr) - one new group mosulite activists determined rebuild city also help rehabilitate fellow residents traumatised events last three years. "there 40 us - we're ambitious, educated, respectable young people love city fellow human beings, want decent future," said. tahani's priority ensure young women like get involved. "we live culture women think it's improper speak up, work outside home lead campaign, true. know girls strong motivated, scared harassment forced stay home families. "people need know girl shameful," continued, arguing culture fear repression "the condition helped come in". tahani got involved ambitious scheme restore mosul university's library, destroyed occupation, delighted encouraging young women defy gender stereotypes. one first enter bombed-out library, remembers seeing "a boy approaching girl carrying five six heavy books. "he said: 'no, don't carry much. it's heavy you, carry can.' said: 'of course carry books, i've come that. please work carry books, i'll carry mine.'" tahani also put together football tournament library project's volunteers, initially forming one men one women, deciding looked much like gender segregation. colleagues' astonishment, mixed teams together - unprecedented move proved successful. "the next day, brought ball, said: 'let's play again.' did." tahani said mosul's physical fabric needed rebuilding; crucial harness young people's enthusiasm freedom first months liberation. "so started cultural events - books, music, festivals, colours, painting, photography. "we wanted draw media attention mosul young person could see image global platform admire realise value." tahani organised first concert city is' defeat, live music played front university campus. "one girls took hand told me: 'tahani, first time feel really alive,'" recalled. together friends, tahani set facebook page called women mosul, place could air views share ideas projects. work young mosulites like tahani seems gaining traction. last month, day-long peace festival set activists drew crowd 25,000 people city's main stadium. tahani said much done, arguing true success would come women felt totally free walk street without wearing hijab, bar selling alcohol could function freely centre city. "only reassured city begun truly accept everyone, accept world." seems long way away, given conservative attitudes still dominant city. many fear former supporters remain city, trying blend civilian population. tahani acknowledges received threats activism, refuses intimidated. "if get scared, i'll return sitting home, won't accept. there's way go back forget hopes dreams, matter price." institute war peace reporting non-profit organisation supports local reporters, citizen journalists civil society activists three dozen countries conflict, crisis transition around world.
