agreed part paris climate deal? deal unites world's nations single agreement tackling climate change first time history. coming consensus among nearly 200 countries need cut greenhouse gas emissions regarded many observers achievement hailed "historic". kyoto protocol 1997 set emission cutting targets handful developed countries, us pulled others failed comply. however, scientists point paris accord must stepped chance curbing dangerous climate change. pledges thus far could see global temperatures rise much 2.7c, agreement lays roadmap speeding progress. what's left out? goal preventing scientists regard dangerous irreversible levels climate change - judged reached around 2c warming pre-industrial times - central agreement. world already nearly halfway almost 1c many countries argued tougher target 1.5c - including leaders low-lying countries face unsustainable sea levels rises warming world. desire ambitious goal kept agreement - promise "endeavour limit" global temperatures even more, 1.5c. dr bill hare, ceo climate analytics, says objective "remarkable". "it victory vulnerable countries, small islands, least developed countries lose, came paris said didn't want sympathy, wanted action." meanwhile, first time, accord lays longer-term plan reaching peak greenhouse emissions "as soon possible" achieving balance output man-made greenhouse gases absorption - forests oceans - "by second half century". "if agreed implemented, means bringing greenhouse-gas emissions net zero within decades. line scientific evidence presented," says john schellnhuber, director potsdam institute climate impact research. described deal "woolly" targets scaled negotiations. "the paris agreement one step long road, parts frustrate disappoint me, progress," says greenpeace international executive director kumi naidoo. "this deal alone won't dig us hole we're in, makes sides less steep." money? money sticking point throughout negotiations. developing countries say need financial technological help leapfrog fossil fuels move straight renewables. currently promised us $100bn (£67bn) year 2020 - much many countries would like. agreement requires rich nations maintain $100bn year funding pledge beyond 2020, use figure "floor" support agreed 2025. deal says wealthy countries continue provide financial support poor nations cope climate change encourages countries join voluntary basis. dr ilan kelman ucl, london, says lack time scales "worrying". "the starting point $100bn per year helpful, remains 8% worldwide declared military spending year." elements paris pact legally binding. national pledges countries cut emissions voluntary, arguments revisit pledges - aim taking tougher action - stumbling block talks. pact promises make assessment progress 2018, reviews every five years. analysts point out, paris beginning shift towards low-carbon world, much do. "paris starting gun race towards low-carbon future," says wwf-uk chief executive david nussbaum. prof john shepherd national oceanography centre, university southampton, says agreement includes welcome aspirations people realise difficult achieve goals. "since mechanism remains voluntary national caps emissions, without even guidance stringent caps would need be, hard optimistic goals likely achieved."
