"tremendously important" rancher coleman locke describes role international trade cattle business. 72-year-old worked family's 10,000-acre ranch gulf coast texas whole life seen fair share struggles industry, including droughts disease. gearing new threat - potential loss trade deals could cut huge slice ranch's yearly sales. "in 2016, 25% breeding stock sold ranch went united states, it's tremendously important market us," says mr locke. he's alone. last year american beef industry earned $6bn (£4.9bn) overseas sales. among biggest purchasers canada mexico, partners us north american free trade agreement (nafta). president trump's promise renegotiate nafta possibly place tariffs mexico us trading partners industry worried. "nafta extremely important us. it's one biggest trade deals agriculture ever had," says john robinson national cattlemen's beef association (ncba). beef industry already reeling loss trans-pacific partnership (tpp), president trump withdrew first week office. free trade agreement pacific rim countries, including many asia, set expand america's export market beef. estimates, could added $400m sales year. "it makes market nervous hear aren't going tpp going change nafta," says jennings steen, cattle dealer based austin. mr steen says partner fielding dozens calls since president trump's election, ranchers desperate know changes trade deals could affect businesses. concerned prices hesitate make long-term plans. american suppliers particularly wanted increased access japan's home market, high tariffs us beef made hard compete suppliers australia sell beef japan lower rates. president trump's supporters say experience business allow negotiate better deals us, focussing bilateral agreements rather bigger deals involving several countries. according texas agriculture commissioner sid miller, 22 years nafta need "facelift". mr miller outspoken early supporter president trump. since election, spent lot time reassuring ranching community trade mexico won'