st, mines seabed would extract far richer ores, covering smaller area immediate impact people - instead killing marine life wherever digging machines deployed potentially devastating far wider area. one major concern effect plumes dust, stirred excavation ocean floor, spreading long distances smothering life wherever settles. understand implications, expedition tropic seamount conducted experiment, first kind, mimic effects mining measure resulting plume. deploying uk research ship james cook, remotely operated vehicle deliberately pumped hundreds litres sediment-filled water every minute robotic sensors positioned downstream ocean current. according dr murton, early results indicate dust hard detect 1km away source plume, suggesting impact mining could localised many fear. comes different disciplines within marine science coming range perspectives emerging development. study led dr daniel jones, also noc, reviewed evidence seabed exploration found wake mining many marine creatures would likely recover within year would return previous levels even two decades. another study focused tiny organisms floor pacific ocean region known clarion-clipperton zone, stretches belt south hawaii. much zone licensed un's international seabed authority companies dozen countries search minerals potato-sized rocks "nodules" lying seabed. prof andy gooday, also noc, colleagues found among metals-rich nodules, far greater diversity single-celled organisms called xenophyophores previously thought. research identified many 34 species lifeforms new science. organisms occupy one lower rungs food chain also play important role forming hard shell-like structures, like miniature coral reefs, provide habitats creatures. prof gooday says range life sediments deep ocean compared tropical rainforest "life ocean floor dynamic" anyone expected. believes unlikely seabed mining would cause species go extinct impact locally would severe. "if eliminate xenophyphores, fragile would certainly destroyed mi